  "prompt": "How far in space have we reached in light years, and what have we found till there?",
  "response": "As of now, humanity's farthest physical reach into space is limited to our robotic spacecraft. The Voyager 1 spacecraft, launched in 1977, is the farthest human-made object from Earth, currently over 14 billion miles away, or approximately 22 billion kilometers. In terms of light-years, Voyager 1 is about 0.0024 light-years from Earth (since 1 light-year is about 5.88 trillion miles or about 9.46 trillion kilometers).\n\nVoyager 1 has significantly contributed to our understanding of the outer planets (Jupiter, Saturn) and their moons, as well as the heliosphere, which is the bubble of solar wind and magnetic fields surrounding our solar system. In 2012, it entered interstellar space, providing valuable data about cosmic rays and the interstellar medium.\n\nOther spacecraft, like Voyager 2, New Horizons (which flew by Pluto in 2015), and the Parker Solar Probe, have also contributed to our knowledge of the solar system, but they, too, are still within a fraction of a light year from Earth.\n\nAs for astronomical discoveries, telescopes such as the Hubble Space Telescope, the Kepler Space Telescope, and more recently the James Webb Space Telescope, have provided insights into distant galaxies, stars, exoplanets, and cosmic phenomena. The light from some of the objects observed by these telescopes has taken billions of years to reach us, meaning we can see objects that are billions of light-years away, offering a glimpse into the early universe.\n\nThough we've reached only a minuscule distance in terms of light-years, our understanding of space has expanded immensely through our observations and the data collected from various missions and telescopes.",
